A continuous random variable \displaystyle X has a chi-square distribution and is referred to as a chi-square random variable if and only if its probability density is given by f(x; 
u) =  egin{cases}\dfrac{1}{2^{\sfrac{
u}{2}} \Gamma(\sfrac{
u}{2})}x^{ rac{
u-2}{2}}e^{-\sfrac{x}{2}}, \amp \quad 	ext{ for }0 \lt x\0, \amp \quad 	ext{elsewhere}\end{cases} where 
u is a parameter describing the number of degrees of freedom.
